The paper discusses compressed sensing and estimation problems in noncoherent information retrieval, which are typically studied in the Information Theory (cs.IT) and Signal Processing (cs.SP) sub-categories. The focus on low-rank and sparse matrices also suggests a connection to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The mention of phase retrieval from intensity Fourier measurements suggests a connection to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the investigation of sparse convolutions as a communication channel model suggests a connection to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category.
